School Daze

Growing up by the Kentish coast, I was quite an adventurous boy. I once tried to cycle all the way from my hometown, Ramsgate, to London without using my hands.

Although that particular stunt ended in a ditch just outside Ramsgate, I later made it to the Big Smoke by other means, receiving a place to study Law at New College of the Humanities.

Uni Years

Although I didn't know it at the time, studying Law would teach me skills for agile software development. The hours I spent examining logic and identifying edge cases come in handy nowadays when I'm reviewing pull requests!

When I graduated three years later, I didn't know what I wanted to do. I was interested in data viz, but I didn't know that it was a career option. All I knew was that I didn't want to be a lawyer! So, naturally...

My Coding Journey

Part 1: Self-teaching

The Pudding. That’s the website that motivated me to start coding. As I'm sure you know, The Pudding is run by a small team of 'journalist-engineers' who publish stories about complex topics using “original datasets, primary research, and interactivity”. The first story that I read back in 2014 was about the size of different rappers’ vocabularies, and it blew my mind. I emailed the author, Matt Daniels, to ask him how he made it.

From the web crawlers that sifted through thousands of song lyrics on Genius.com, to the data viz library (D3.js) that he'd used to present the findings, Matt's story used the power of web to its fullest.

I was itching play with these technologies myself. So, I started learning how to code.

Coding had always seemed suspiciously like magic to me. So, you can imagine how I felt when, at 7:32pm on 24 December 2017, I saw the words ‘Hello world!’ materialise on my Macbook command line.

CLICK TO TEAR

I was hooked. Finally, I knew what I wanted to do: develop interactive web experiences!

I got my first chance when my idea for a research project got picked up at work. I wrote a simple Python web scraper, used it to gather the data, and found a story somewhere in the mix. Feel free to read my write up!

Part 2: Founders and Coders

In early 2019, I got accepted onto Founders and Coders, a selective coding bootcamp that focuses on JavaScript fundamentals and peer-led learning. I spent the next four months living and breathing code, building full stack web apps with Node.js, PostgreSQL, React, and more. By the time I was done, I'd learned more than I'd thought possible just a few months earlier. And I was only just getting started...

CLICK TO TEAR

Case Study: LsX Action Planner

I was the UX Lead in a four-person dev team on a web app for a London-based charity. We had three weeks to turn our product owner's idea into a Minimum Viable Product (MVP). For the one-week design sprint, we followed a modified version of the Google Ventures Design Sprint. For the two development sprints, we adopted agile ceremonies.

The (Dream) Team

The Client

London Sustainability Exchange (LSx) works with schools, communities, and London policy makers to raise awareness around the problem of air pollution. Their aim is to use citizen science to help make the invisible, visible.

Stage 1: Discovery

We met with Jack, our product owner from LsX, to learn about his goals. We gathered information about the different stakeholders whom LsX serves, and we drafted a survey of user research questions for Jack to ask his potential users in order to interrogate his assumptions about their needs. Based on the findings of this research, we were able to identify a clear problem to develop a solution for.

The Problem

School children need a way to be remotely supported when conducting air quality experiments and drawing conclusions so they can mobilise and feel confident in creating effective action plans.

Stage 2: Definition

We met with Jack a second time to brainstorm different solutions to the problem. We spent a day sketching out different representations of what the final product could look like, adding the most popular ideas to a storyboard as we went along. By the end of the day, we had a solid step-by-step plan for our prototype.

The Solution

A Progressive Web App (PWA) to enable children to facilitate change by creating an air pollution action plan.

Stage 3: Prototyping

We decided to use Figma, a design tool known for its versatility, for wire framing and prototyping. We started by scaffolding low fidelity wireframes of the most important screens in our app. We discussed the merits of different UI configurations, and we iterated rapidly to finish a rough working prototype that was ready to test with users.

User Testing

My favourite piece of feedback came from a user who said the app gave him "back-of-children's-cereal-box vibes".

Many of our users knew about other air quality apps, but none that help you to make an action plan. We decided to double down on making this feature our USP.

Stage 4: Sprint Planning

After modifying our prototype in response to user feedback, we began sprint planning. We defined our user stories (with acceptance criteria) and raised GitHub issues for each one. We linked each issue to a GitHub Projects board, which we used to track of our progress on different features.

We knew that we'd be reusing certain UI components across multiple pages of our app, so using React with Styled Components seemed like a great choice for writing front end code that would be modular and reusable.

More User Testing

During the second round of user testing (this time with children), we noticed that some users confused parts of background images for clickable UI elements. We realised we needed to make these elements stand out more.

Stage 5: Sprint Retrospective + Sprint Planning

At the end of the week, we had a team retrospective. This was a great chance to reflect on the highs and lows from our first build sprint, enabling us to plan even more effectively for the second one. With renewed focus on our core user stories, we entered the final sprint with a spring in our step and our MVP in sight.

The Final Push

During our second build sprint, we added a key feature that would allow users of our app to email their action plans to themselves. We set aside a day at the end of the sprint for final bugfixing before the product handover.

Stage 6: Product Handover

We met with our product owner to demo the finished MVP and give him documentation on how to use it. He gave us this feedback:

"I was so impressed with the team I worked with. I was expecting strong technical support but was blown away by the quality of joined-up thinking. The team really understood our charity, our needs, and were really creative about how an app would be able to extend our work."

Jack Alexander - Projects Officer at London Sustainability Exchange

Part 3: Mentoring

Since finishing Founders and Coders in June, I've remained involved in the community; first, as a mentor in the classroom, and, more recently, as the course facilitator.

My approach to mentoring is that you don't need to know all the answers to help someone learn how to code (in fact, mentoring has opened my eyes to many gaps in my own knowledge!). My favourite technique is 'rubber ducking' - listening while a student talks me through some code they've written. I also write blog posts about coding concepts that challenged me when I was starting out. It's amazing what explaining something to someone else can do for to improve your own understanding of a topic!
